{{short description|Academic movement regarding society, race and culture in the United States}}
{{pp|small=yes}}
{{Use American English|date=June 2021}}
{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2021}}
'''Critical race theory''' ('''CRT''') is a cross-disciplinary intellectual movement that began in the United States in the post-civil rights era as 1960s landmark civil rights laws were being eroded and schools were being re-segregated.<ref>{{harvnb|Ansell|2008|pp=344–345}}; {{harvnb|The Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica|2021}}; {{harvnb|Bridges|2019|p=7}}; {{harvnb|Crenshaw|Gotanda|Peller|Thomas|1995|p=xiii}}.</ref> With racial inequalities persisting even after civil rights legislation was enacted, CRT scholars in the 1970s and 1980s began reworking and expanding [[critical legal studies]]' (CLS) theories on class and economic structure and the law<ref>{{harvnb|Ansell|2008|p=344}}; {{harvnb|Cole|2007|pp=112–113|ps=: "CRT was a reaction to Critical Legal Studies (CLS)&nbsp;... CRT was a response to CLS, criticizing the latter for its undue emphasis on class and economic structure, and insisting that 'race' is a more critical identity."}}</ref> to focus on the relationship between racial inequality and the law in the U.S.{{sfn|Bridges|2021|loc=2:06}} They said that the liberal notion of value-neutral U.S. laws had a significant political role in maintaining a racially unjust social order,{{sfn|Ansell|2008|pp=344–345}} where formally [[Color blindness (racial classification)|color-blind]] laws continue to have [[Discrimination based on skin color|racially discriminatory]] outcomes.<ref name="Crenshaw 2019">{{Cite book |last=Crenshaw |first=Kimberlé Williams |title=Seeing Race Again: Countering Colorblindness across the Disciplines |chapter=Unmasking Colorblindness in the Law: Lessons from the Formation of Critical Race Theory |date=2019 |pages=52–84 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=978-0-520-97214-8 |doi=10.1525/9780520972148-004 |jstor=j.ctvcwp0hd |s2cid=243191319}}</ref> 

One tenet of CRT in the current multidisciplinary and international form, is that racism and disparate racial outcomes are the result of complex, changing, and often subtle social and institutional dynamics, rather than explicit and intentional prejudices of individuals.<ref name="Gillborn 2020">{{cite book |last1=Gillborn |first1=David |last2=Ladson-Billings |first2=Gloria |display-editors=1 |editor1=Paul Atkinson |editor2=Sara Delamont |editor3=Alexandru Cernat |editor4=Joseph W. Sakshaug |editor5=Richard A. Williams |chapter=Critical Race Theory |date=2020 |title=SAGE Research Methods Foundations |publisher=SAGE Publications |doi=10.4135/9781526421036764633 |isbn=978-1-5264-2103-6 |s2cid=240846071 |series=Theoretical Foundations of Qualitative Research}}</ref>{{r|Iati}}{{sfn|Bridges|2019}} 

CRT is a framework of analysis grounded in [[critical theory]]{{sfn|Crenshaw|Gotanda|Peller|Thomas|1995|p=xxvii}} which originated in the mid-1970s in the writings of several American legal scholars, including [[Derrick Bell]], Alan Freeman, [[Kimberlé Crenshaw]], [[Richard Delgado]], [[Cheryl Harris]], Charles R. Lawrence III, [[Mari Matsuda]], and [[Patricia J. Williams]].{{sfn|Ansell|2008|p=344}} CRT draws from thinkers such as [[Antonio Gramsci]], [[Sojourner Truth]], [[Frederick Douglass]], and [[W. E. B. DuBois]], as well as the [[Black Power]], [[Chicano]], and [[radical feminist]] movements from the 1960s and 1970s.{{sfn|Ansell|2008|p=344}}

Scholars of CRT view race as a [[Social constructionism|social construct]] that is not "biologically grounded and natural";{{sfn|Curry|2009a|p=166}}<ref name="Gillborn 2020" /> and that race as a construct advances the interests of [[white people]]{{sfn|Curry|2009a|p=166}} at the expense of people of color.<ref name="Milner 2013">{{cite journal |last1=Milner |first1=Richard |title=Analyzing Poverty, Learning, and Teaching Through a Critical Race Theory Lens |journal=Review of Research in Education |volume=37 |issue=1 |pages=1–53 |date=March 2013 |issn=1935-1038 |doi=10.3102/0091732X12459720 |jstor=24641956}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Crenshaw|1991}}; {{harvnb|Crenshaw|1989}}.</ref> A key CRT concept is [[intersectionality]], which emphasizes that race can combine with other identities (such as gender and class) to produce complex combinations of power and advantage.<ref name="Gillborn 2021">{{Cite journal |last=Gillborn |first=David |date=2015 |title=Intersectionality, Critical Race Theory, and the Primacy of Racism: Race, Class, Gender, and Disability in Education |journal=Qualitative Inquiry |volume=21 |issue=3 |pages=277–287 |doi=10.1177/1077800414557827 |s2cid=147260539 |issn=1077-8004}}</ref>

Academic critics of CRT argue that it is based on [[storytelling]] instead of evidence and reason, rejects the concepts of truth and merit, and opposes [[liberalism]].<ref>{{harvnb|The Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica|2021}}; {{harvnb|Cabrera|2018|p=213}}.</ref> In the 21st century, CRT has generated some political controversies. 
Since 2020, conservative U.S. lawmakers have sought to [[Censoring of school curricula in the United States|ban or restrict the instruction]] of CRT along with other [[Anti-racism|anti{{nbh}}racism]] education in [[Primary school|primary]] and [[Secondary school|secondary]] schools.{{r|Iati|Wallace-Wells}} These lawmakers have been accused of misrepresenting the tenets and importance of CRT and of having the goal of broadly silencing discussions of racism, equality, [[social justice]], and the history of race.<ref name="Bump 2021">{{Cite news |last=Bump |first=Philip |title=Analysis {{!}} The Scholar Strategy: How 'critical race theory' alarms could convert racial anxiety into political energy |work=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2021/06/15/scholar-strategy-how-critical-race-theory-alarms-could-convert-racial-anxiety-into-political-energy/ |date=June 15, 2021 |issn=0190-8286 |url-access=limited |archive-date=June 22, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210622025034/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2021/06/15/scholar-strategy-how-critical-race-theory-alarms-could-convert-racial-anxiety-into-political-energy/ |url-status=}}</ref>{{sfn|Harris|2021}}

{{Toclimit|3}}

==Definitions==
In 2021, [[Khiara Bridges]], a law professor and author of the textbook, ''Critical Race Theory: A Primer'',{{sfn|Bridges|2019}} defined critical race theory as an "intellectual movement"{{emdash}}a "body of scholarship", and an "analytical toolset for interrogating the relationship between law and racial inequality."{{sfn|Bridges|2021|loc=2:06}}

In his introduction to the comprehensive 1995 publication of critical race theory's key writings, [[Cornel West]] describes CRT as "an intellectual movement that is both particular to our postmodern (and conservative) times and part of a long tradition of human resistance and liberation."{{sfn|West|1995|p=xi}} 

Law professor Roy L. Brooks defined critical race theory in 1994 as "a collection of critical stances against the existing legal order from a race-based point of view".{{sfn|Brooks|1994|p=85}} ''[[Education Week]]'' describes the core of CRT as the idea that race is a [[Social constructionism|social construct]] and [[racism]] is neither an individual bias nor prejudice{{emdash}}it is "embedded in the legal system" and supplemented with policies and procedures.<ref name="Sawchuk 2021">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.edweek.org/leadership/what-is-critical-race-theory-and-why-is-it-under-attack/2021/05 |title=What Is Critical Race Theory, and Why Is It Under Attack? |first=Stephen |last=Sawchuk |date=May 18, 2021 |access-date=November 10, 2021 |magazine=Education Week |url-access=limited}}</ref>

[[University of Alabama School of Law]] professor [[Richard Delgado]], a co-founder of critical race theory, and legal writer [[Jean Stefancic]] define CRT as "a collection of activists and scholars interested in studying and transforming the relationship among race, racism, and power".<ref>{{harvnb|Cabrera|2018|p=211}}; {{harvnb|Delgado|Stefancic|2017|p=3}}.</ref>

[[Gloria Ladson-Billings]], who{{emdash}}along with co-author William Tate{{emdash}}had introduced CRT to the field of education in 1995,{{snf|Ladson-Billings|Tate|1995}} described CRT it as an "interdisciplinary approach that seeks to understand and combat race inequity in society."{{snf|Ladson-Billings|1998}}<ref name="Gillborn 2021"/> Ladson-Billings wrote in 1998 that CRT "first emerged as a counterlegal scholarship to the positivist and liberal legal discourse of civil rights."{{snf|Ladson-Billings|1998|p=7}}

The editors of the ''Encyclopaedia Britannica'' describe CRT as an "intellectual and social movement and loosely organized framework of legal analysis".{{sfn|The Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica|2021}} In the video that accompanies the article, CRT is defined as a "way of thinking about the world, especially the social norms and legal practices that govern society".{{sfn|"Examine critical race theory (CRT)"}}

CRT is a "framework that can be used to theorize, examine and challenge the ways race and racism implicitly and explicitly impact on social structures, practices and discourses", according to [[Tara J. Yosso]].{{sfn|Yosso|2005|pp=70–71}}

==Tenets==
Scholars of CRT say that race is not "biologically grounded and natural";{{sfn|Curry|2009a|p=166}}<ref name="Gillborn 2020" /> rather, it is a socially constructed category used to oppress and exploit people of color;{{sfn|"Examine critical race theory (CRT)"}} and that racism is not an aberration,{{sfn|Bell|1992}} but a normalized feature of American society.{{sfn|"Examine critical race theory (CRT)"}} 
According to CRT, negative stereotypes assigned to members of minority groups "benefit white people"{{sfn|"Examine critical race theory (CRT)"}} and increase racial oppression.{{sfn|McCristal-Culp|1992|p=1149}}
Individuals can belong to a number of different identity groups.{{sfn|"Examine critical race theory (CRT)"}} The concept of [[intersectionality]]{{emdash}}one of CRT's main concepts{{emdash}}was introduced by legal scholar Kimberlé Crenshaw.{{sfn|Crenshaw|1989}}{{sfn|Hancock|2016|p=192}}

[[Derrick Bell|Derrick Albert Bell]] Jr. (1930 – 2011), an American lawyer, professor, and [[civil rights activist]], writes that racial equality is "impossible and illusory" and that racism in the U.S. is permanent.{{sfn|Bell|1992}}
According to Bell, civil-rights legislation will not on its own bring about progress in race relations;{{sfn|Bell|1992}} alleged improvements or advantages to people of color "tend to serve the interests of dominant white groups", in what Bell calls "interest convergence".{{sfn|"Examine critical race theory (CRT)"}} These changes do not typically affect{{emdash}}and at times even reinforce{{emdash}}racial hierarchies.{{sfn|"Examine critical race theory (CRT)"}} This is representative of the shift in the 1970s, in Bell's re-assessment of his earlier desegregation work as a civil rights lawyer. He was responding to the Supreme Court's decisions that had resulted in the re-segregation of schools.{{sfn|Bell|1980}}{{sfn|Cesario|2008|pp=201-212}}

The concept of [[standpoint theory]], introduced by feminist sociologists in the 1980s, was expanded to include a black feminist standpoint by [[Patricia Hill Collins]]. People in marginalized groups, who share similar experiences, can bring a collective wisdom and a unique voice to discussions on decreasing oppression.{{sfn|Hill Collins|2002}}{{sfn|Harnois|2020}} In this view, insights into racism can be uncovered by examining the nature of the U.S. legal system through the perspective of the everyday lived experiences of people of color.{{sfn|"Examine critical race theory (CRT)"}} 

According to ''Encyclopedia Britannica'', tenets of CRT have spread beyond academia, and are used to deepen understanding of socio-economic issues such as "poverty, police brutality, and voting rights violations", that are impacted by the ways in which race and racism are "understood and misunderstood" in the United States.{{sfn|"Examine critical race theory (CRT)"}}

==Early years==
In the 1998 article, "Critical Race Theory: Past, Present, and Future", Delgado and Stefancic trace the origins of CRT to the early writings of Derrick Albert Bell Jr. including his 1976 ''[[Yale Law Journal]]'' article, "Serving Two Masters"<ref>{{harvnb|Delgado|Stefancic|1998a|p=467}}; {{harvnb|Delgado|Stefancic|2001|p=30}}; {{harvnb|Bell|1976}}.</ref> and his 1980 ''[[Harvard Law Review]]'' article entitled "Brown v. Board of Education and the Interest-Convergence Dilemma".<ref>{{harvnb|Delgado|Stefancic|1998a}}; {{harvnb|Bell|1980}}.</ref><ref name="Friedman 2021">{{Cite report |publisher=PEN America |last=Friedman |first=Jonathan |title=Educational Gag Orders: Legislative Restrictions on the Freedom to Read, Learn, and Teach |location=New York |date=November 8, 2021 |url=https://pen.org/report/educational-gag-orders/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211109185512/https://pen.org/report/educational-gag-orders/ |archive-date=November 9, 2021}}</ref> 

In the 1970s, as a professor at [[Harvard Law School]] Bell began to critique, question and re-assess the civil rights cases he had legislated in the 1960s to desegregate schools following the passage of ''[[Brown v. Board of Education]]''.{{sfn|Bell|1980}} This re-assessment became the "cornerstone of critical race theory".{{sfn|Wright|2021}} Delgado and Stefancic, who together wrote ''Critical Race Theory: a Introduction'' in 2001,{{sfn|Delgado|Stefancic|2001}} described Bell's "interest convergence" as a "means of understanding Western racial history".{{sfn|Delgado|Stefancic|1998a|p=467}} The focus on desegregation after the 1954 Supreme Court decision in ''Brown''{{emdash}}declaring school segregation unconstitutional{{emdash}}left "civil-rights lawyers compromised between their clients' interests and the law". The concern of many Black parents{{emdash}}for their children's access to better education{{emdash}}was being eclipsed by the interests of litigators who wanted a "breakthrough"{{sfn|Delgado|Stefancic|1998a|p=467}} in their "pursuit of racial balance in schools".<ref name="Jackson 2021">{{Cite magazine |last=Jackson |first=Lauren Michele |title=The Void That Critical Race Theory Was Created to Fill |magazine=The New Yorker |access-date=November 8, 2021 |date=July 7, 2021 |url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/cultural-comment/the-void-that-critical-race-theory-was-created-to-fill |url-access=limited}}</ref> In 1995, [[Cornel West]] said that Bell was "virtually the lone dissenter" writing in leading law reviews who challenged basic assumptions about how the law treated people of color.{{West|1995}}

In his ''Harvard Law Review'' articles, Bell cites the 1964 [[Hudson v. Leake County School Board]] case which the LDF won, mandating that the all-white school board comply with desegregation. At that time it was seen as a success. By the 1970s, white parents were removing their children from the desegregated schools and enrolling them in [[segregation academies]].<ref>{{harvnb|Bell|1976}}; {{harvnb|Bell|1980}}.</ref> Bell came to believe that he had been mistaken in 1964 when, as a young lawyer working for the LDF, he had convinced [[Winson Hudson]], who was the head of the newly-formed local NAACP chapter in Harmony, Mississippi, to fight the all-white Leake County School Board to desegregate schools.<ref name="Cobb 2021"/> She and the other Black parents had initially sought LDF assistance to fight the board's closure of their school{{emdash}}one of the historic [[Rosenwald Schools]] for Black children.<ref name="Cobb 2021">{{Cite news |issn=0028-792X |last=Cobb |first=Jelani |title=The Man Behind Critical Race Theory |work=The New Yorker |access-date=November 14, 2021 |date=September 13, 2021 |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2021/09/20/the-man-behind-critical-race-theory |url-access=limited}}</ref>{{sfn|Wright|2021}} Bell explained to Hudson, that{{emdash}}following ''Brown''{{emdash}}the LDF could not fight to keep a segregated Black school open; they would have to fight for desegregation.<ref>{{harvnb|Wright|2021}}; {{harvnb|Bell|1976}}; {{harvnb|Bell|1980}}.</ref> In 1964, Bell and the NAACP had believed that resources for desegregated schools would be increased and Black children would access higher quality education, since white parents would insist on better quality schools; by the 1970s, Black children were again attending segregated schools and the quality of education had deteriorated.<ref>{{harvnb|Wright|2021}}; {{harvnb|Bell|1976}}; {{harvnb|Bell|1980}}.</ref>

Bell began to work for the NAACP LDF shortly after the [[Montgomery bus boycott]] and the ensuing 1956 Supreme Court ruling following ''[[Browder v. Gayle]]'' that the Alabama and Montgomery bus segregation laws were unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.crmvet.org/tim/timhis55.htm#1955mbb |title=Montgomery Bus Boycott |website=Civil Rights Movement Archive}}</ref> From 1960 to 1966 Bell successfully litigated 300 civil rights cases in Mississippi. Bell was inspired by [[Thurgood Marshall]], who had been one of the two leaders of a decades-long legal campaign starting in the 1930s, in which they filed hundreds of lawsuits to reverse the "[[separate but equal]]" doctrine announced by the Supreme Court's decision in ''[[Plessy v. Ferguson]]'' (1896). The Court ruled that [[racial segregation]] laws enacted by the states were not in violation of the [[United States Constitution]] as long as the facilities for each race were equal in quality.<ref name="Groves 1951">{{cite journal |last=Groves |first=Harry E. |year=1951 |title=Separate but Equal—The Doctrine of Plessy v. Ferguson |journal=Phylon |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=66–72 |doi=10.2307/272323 |jstor=272323}}</ref> The ''Plessy'' decision provided the legal mandate at the federal level to enforce [[Jim Crow laws]] that had been introduced by white [[Southern Democrat]]s starting in the 1870s for racial segregation in all public facilities, including public schools. The Court's 1954 ''Brown'' decision{{emdash}}which held that the "separate but equal" doctrine is unconstitutional in the context of public schools and educational facilities{{emdash}}severely weakened ''Plessy''.<ref name="Schauer 1997">{{cite journal |last1=Schauer |first1=Frederick |author-link=Frederick Schauer |title=Generality and Equality |journal=Law and Philosophy |date=1997 |volume=16 |issue=3 |pages=279–97 |jstor=3504874}}</ref> The Supreme Court concept of [[constitutional colorblindness]] in regards to case evaluation began with ''Plessy''. Before ''Plessy'', the Court considered color as a determining factor in many landmark cases, which reinforced Jim Crow laws.{{sfn|Gotanda|1991}} Bell's 1960s civil rights work built on Justice Marshall's groundwork begun in the 1930s. It was time when the legal branch of the civil rights movement was launching thousands of civil rights cases. It was a period of idealism for the civil rights movement.{{sfn|Wright|2021}} 

At Harvard, Bell developed new courses that studied American law through a racial lens. He compiled his own course materials which were published in 1970 under the title, ''Race, racism, and American law''.{{sfn|Bell|1970}} He became Harvard Law School's first Black tenured professor in 1971.<ref name="Jackson 2021"/> 

During the 1970s, the courts were using legislation to enforce affirmative action programs and busing{{emdash}}where the courts mandated busing to achieve racial integration in school districts that rejected desegregation. In response, in the 1970s, neoconservative think tanks{{emdash}}hostile to these two issues in particular{{emdash}}developed a color-blind rhetoric to oppose them,{{sfn|Crenshaw|1988|p=103}} claiming they represented reverse discrimination. In 1978, ''[[Regents of the University of California v. Bakke]]'', when Bakke won this landmark Supreme Court case by using the argument of [[reverse racism]], Bell's skepticism that racism would end increased. Justice [[Lewis F. Powell Jr.]] held that the "guarantee of equal protection cannot mean one thing when applied to one individual and something else when applied to a person of another color." In a 1979 article, Bell asked if there were any groups of the white population that would be willing to suffer any disadvantage that might result from the implementation of a policy to rectify harms to Black people resulting from slavery, segregation, or discrimination.{{sfn|Bell|1979a}} 

Bell resigned in 1980 because of what he viewed as the university's discriminatory practices,{{sfn|Harris|2021}} became the dean at [[University of Oregon School of Law]] and later returned to Harvard as a visiting professor. 

While he was absent from Harvard, his supporters organized protests against Harvard's lack of [[racial diversity]] in the [[curriculum]], in the student body and in the faculty.{{sfn|Crenshaw|Gotanda|Peller|Thomas|1995|pp=xix–xx}}{{r|Buras 2014}} The university had rejected student requests, saying no sufficiently qualified black instructor existed.{{sfn|Crenshaw|Gotanda|Peller|Thomas|1995|page=xx|ps=: "The liberal white Harvard administration responded to student protests, demonstrations, rallies, and sit-ins{{emdash}}including a takeover of the Dean's office{{emdash}}by asserting that there were no qualified black scholars who merited Harvard's interest."}} Legal scholar Randall Kennedy writes that some students had "felt affronted" by Harvard's choice to employ an "archetypal white liberal... in a way that precludes the development of black leadership".<ref name="Kennedy 1989">{{cite journal |last1=Kennedy |first1=Randall L. |title=Racial Critiques of Legal Academia |journal=Harvard Law Review |date=June 1989 |volume=102 |issue=8 |pages=1745–1819 |doi=10.2307/1341357 |jstor=1341357 |url=https://harvardlawreview.org/2020/10/racial-critiques-of-legal-academia/}}</ref> 

One of these students was Kimberlé Crenshaw, who had chosen Harvard in order to study under Bell; she was introduced to his work at Cornell.{{sfn|Cook|Martinez Hosang|Ladson-Billings|Peller|2021|loc=c.14:36}} Crenshaw organized the student-led initiative to offer an alternative course on race and law in 1981{{emdash}}based on Bell's course and textbook{{emdash}}where students brought in visiting professors, such as Charles Lawrence, Linda Greene, Neil Gotanda, and Richard Delgado,<ref name="Jackson 2021"/> to teach chapter by chapter from ''Race, racism, and American law''.{{sfn|Cook|Martinez Hosang|Ladson-Billings|Peller|2021}}<ref name="Gottesman 2016">{{Cite book|last=Gottesman|first=Isaac|title=The Critical Turn in Education: From Marxist Critique to Poststructuralist Feminism to Critical Theories of Race|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=2016|isbn=978-1-3176-7095-7|location=London|pages=123|chapter=Critical Race Theory and Legal Studies}}</ref>{{sfn|Crenshaw|Gotanda|Peller|Thomas|1995|pp=xix–xx}}<ref name="Buras 2014">{{cite book |last1=Buras |first1=Kristen L. |editor-last1=Dixson |editor-first1=Adrienne D. |title=Researching Race in Education: Policy, Practice, and Qualitative Research |date=2014 |publisher=Information Age Publishing |location=Charlotte, N.C. |isbn=978-1-6239-6678-2 |pages=49–50 |chapter=From Carter G. Woodson to Critical Race Curriculum Studies |quote=When Bell departed from Harvard to lead the University of Oregon School of Law, Harvard's law students of color demanded that another faculty member of color be hired to replace him.}}</ref> 

Critical race theory emerged as an intellectual movement with the organization of this boycott; CRT scholars included graduate law students and professors.{{sfn|Ansell|2008|p=344}} 

Alan Freeman was a founding member of the Critical Legal Studies (CLS) movement that hosted forums in the 1980s. CLS legal scholars challenged claims to the alleged value-neutral position of the law. They criticized the legal system's role in generating and legitimizing oppressive social structures which contributed to maintaining an unjust and oppressive class system.{{sfn|Ansell|2008|p=344}} Delgado and Stefancic cite the work of Alan Freeman in the 1970s as formative to critical race theory.{{sfn|Delgado|Stefancic|2001|p=30}} In his 1978 ''Minnesota Law Review'' article Freeman reinterpreted, through a critical legal studies perspective, how the Supreme Court oversaw civil rights legislation from 1953 to 1969 under the [[Warren Court]]. He criticized the narrow interpretation of the law which denied relief for victims of racial discrimination.<ref name="Freeman 1978">{{Cite journal |last=Freeman |first=Alan David |title=Legitimizing Racial Discrimination through Antidiscrimination law: A Critical Review of Supreme Court Doctrine |journal=Minnesota Law Review |date=January 1, 1978 |volume=62 |number=73}}</ref> In his article, Freeman describes two perspectives on the concept of racial discrimination: that of victim or perpetrator. Racial discrimination to the victim includes both objective conditions and the "consciousness associated with those objective conditions". To the perpetrator, racial discrimination consists only of actions without consideration of the objective conditions experienced by the victims, such as the "lack of jobs, lack of money, lack of housing".<ref name="Freeman 1978"/> Only those individuals who could prove they were victims of discrimination were deserving of remedies.{{sfn|Crenshaw|1988|p=104-105}} By the late 1980s, Freeman, Bell, and other CRT scholars left the CLS movement claiming it was too narrowly focused on class and economic structures while neglecting the role of race and race relations in American law.{{sfn|Yosso|2005|p=71}}

==Emergence as a movement==
{{Third-party|section|date=November 2021}}

In 1989, Kimberlé Crenshaw, Neil Gotanda, and Stephanie Phillips organized a workshop at the [[University of Wisconsin-Madison]] entitled "New Developments in Critical Race Theory". The organizers coined the term "Critical Race Theory" to be an "intersection of critical theory and race, racism, and the law."{{West|1995|xxvii}} 

Following this meeting, legal scholars began publishing a higher volume of works employing critical race theory, including over "300 leading law review articles" and books.<ref name="Ladson-Billings 2021">{{Cite book |last=Ladson-Billings |first=Gloria |title=Critical Race Theory in Education: A Scholar's Journey |date=2021 |publisher=Teachers College Press |isbn=978-0-8077-6583-8}}</ref>{{rp|108}} In 1990, Duncan Kennedy published his article on affirmative action in legal academia in the ''Duke Law Journal'',{{sfn|Kennedy|1990}} and Anthony E. Cook published his article "Beyond Critical Legal Studies" in the ''Harvard Law Review''.<ref name="Cook 1990">{{Cite journal |doi=10.2307/1341453 |issn=0017-811X |volume=103 |issue=5 |pages=985–1044 |last=Cook |first=Anthony E. |title=Beyond Critical Legal Studies: The Reconstructive Theology of Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. |journal=Harvard Law Review |date=1990 |url=http://www.xroads.virginia.edu/~ug03/dumlao/civilrights/cook.beyond-critical-legal-studies.pdf |jstor=1341453 |archive-date=November 12, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211112170252/http://www.xroads.virginia.edu/~ug03/dumlao/civilrights/cook.beyond-critical-legal-studies.pdf}}</ref> In 1991, Patricia Williams published ''[[The Alchemy of Race and Rights]]'', while Derrick Bell published ''Faces at the Bottom of the Well'' in 1992.<ref name="Gottesman 2016" />{{rp|124}} Cheryl I. Harris published her 1993 ''Harvard Law Review'' article "Whiteness as Property" in which she described how [[Passing (racial identity)|passing]] led to benefits akin to owning property.{{sfn|Harris|1993}}<ref name="Warren 1993">{{Cite news |last=Warren |first=James |title='Whiteness as Property' |work=Chicago Tribune |date=September 5, 1993 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1993-09-05-9309050031-story.html}}</ref> In 1995, two dozen legal scholars contributed to a major compilation of key writings on critical race theory.{{sfn|Crenshaw|Gotanda|Peller|Thomas|1995|p=xiii}} 

By the early 1990s, key concepts and features of CRT had emerged. Bell had introduced his concept of "interest convergence" in his 1973 article.<ref>{{harvnb|Delgado|Stefancic|1998a}}; {{harvnb|Bell|1980}}.</ref> He developed the concept of racial realism in a 1992 series of essays and book, ''Faces at the bottom of the well: the permanence of racism.''{{sfn|Bell|1992}} He said that Black people needed to accept that the civil rights era legislation would not on its own bring about progress in race relations; anti-Black racism in the U.S. was a "permanent fixture" of American society; and equality was "impossible and illusory" in the US. Crenshaw had introduced and developed the concept of intersectionality in her 1989 article in the ''University of Chicago Legal Forum''{{sfn|Crenshaw|1989}} and her 1990 article in the ''Stanford Law Review''.{{sfn|Crenshaw|1991}}<ref name="Gillborn 2021"/>

In 1995, pedagogical theorists Gloria Ladson-Billings and William F. Tate began applying the critical race theory framework in the field of education.{{snf|Ladson-Billings|Tate|1995}}{{sfn|Ladson-Billings|1998|pp=7-24}}{{Curry|2008|pp=35-36}} In their 1995 article Ladson-Billings and Tate described the role of the social construction of white norms and interests in education. They sought to better understand inequities in schooling. Scholars have since expanded work to explore issues including [[School segregation in the United States|school segregation in the U.S.]]; relations between race, gender, and academic achievement; [[pedagogy]]; and [[research methodologies]].<ref name="Donnor 2017">{{cite book |author1-last=Donnor |author1-first=Jamel |author2-last=Ladson-Billings |author2-first=Gloria |editor1-last=Denzin |editor1-first=Norman |editor2-last=Lincoln |editor2-first=Yvonna |title=The SAGE handbook of qualitative research |year=2017 |publisher=Sage Publications |location=Thousand Oaks, California |isbn=978-1-4833-4980-0 |edition=Fifth |chapter=Critical Race Theory and the Postracial Imaginary |page=366}}</ref>

{{As of|2002}}, over 20 [[Law school in the United States|American law schools]] and at least three non-American [[law school]]s offered critical race theory courses or classes.{{sfn|Harris|2002|p=1216|ps=: "Over twenty American law schools offer courses in Critical Race Theory or include Critical Race Theory as a central part of other courses. Critical Race Theory is a formal course in a number of universities in the United States and in at least three foreign law schools."}} Critical race theory is also applied in the fields of [[Education Studies|education]], [[political science]], [[women's studies]], [[ethnic studies]], [[Communication studies|communication]], [[Sociology of race and ethnic relations|sociology]], and [[American studies]]. Other movements developed that apply critical race theory to specific groups. These include the Latino-critical (LatCrit), queer-critical, and Asian-critical movements. These continued to engage with the main body of critical theory research, over time developing independent priorities and research methods.{{sfn|Delgado|Stefancic|2017|pp=7–8}} CRT has also been taught internationally, including in the United Kingdom and Australia.<ref name="Birmingham">{{cite web |title=Critical Race Theory |publisher=Centre for Research in Race and Education; University of Birmingham |url=https://www.birmingham.ac.uk/research/crre/critical-race-theory/index.aspx |access-date=June 25, 2021}}</ref><ref name="Quinn 2020">{{cite web |last=Quinn |first=Karl |title=Are all white people racist? Why Critical Race Theory has us rattled |website=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=November 6, 2020 |url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/books/are-all-white-people-racist-why-critical-race-theory-has-us-rattled-20201105-p56bwv.html |access-date=June 26, 2021 |url-access=limited}}</ref>

==Philosophical underpinnings==
CRT scholars draw on the work of [[Antonio Gramsci]], [[Sojourner Truth]], [[Frederick Douglass]], and [[W. E. B. DuBois]]. Bell shared Paul Robeson's belief that "Black self-reliance and African cultural continuity should form the epistemic basis of Blacks' worldview."{{sfn|Curry|2012|p=4}}
Their writing is also informed by the 1960s and 1970s movements such as [[Black Power]], [[Chicano]], and [[radical feminist]].{{sfn|Ansell|2008|p=344}} Critical race theory shares many intellectual commitments with critical theory, critical legal studies, [[feminist legal theory|feminist jurisprudence]], and [[postcolonial theory]]. [[University of Connecticut]] philosopher, [[Lewis Gordon]], who has focuse on postcolonial phenomenology, and race and racism, wrote that CRT is notable for its use postmodern poststructural scholarship, including an emphasis on "subaltern" or "marginalized" communities and the "use of alternative methodology in the expression of theoretical work, most notably their use of "narratives" and other literary techniques".{{sfn|Gordon|1999}}

Standpoint theory, which has been adopted by some CRT scholars, emerged from the first wave of the women's movement in the 1970s. The main focus of feminist standpoint theory is epistemology{{emdash}}the study of how knowledge is produced. The term was coined by [[Sandra Harding]], an American feminist theorist, and developed by [[Dorothy E. Smith|Dorothy Smith]] in her 1989 publication, ''The Everyday World as Problematic: A Feminist Sociology''.<ref name="Borland">{{Cite encyclopedia |last=Borland |first=Elizabeth |title=Standpoint theory |encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Britannica |access-date=November 22, 2021 |url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/standpoint-theory |url-access=limited}}</ref> Smith wrote that by studying how women socially construct their own everyday life experiences, sociologists could ask new questions.<ref name="Macionis 2011">{{cite book |last1=Macionis |first1=John J. |last2=Gerber |first2=Linda M. |title=Sociology |publisher=Pearson Prentice Hall |location=Toronto |year=2011 |page=12 |edition=7th Canadian |isbn=978-0-13-800270-1}}</ref><ref name="Lukács 1971">{{cite book |last=Lukács |first=György |title=History and class consciousness: studies in Marxist dialectics |publisher=MIT Press |location=London, UK Cambridge, Massachusetts |year=1990 |orig-year=1971 |isbn=978-0-85036-197-1}}</ref> [[Patricia Hill Collins]] introduced black feminist standpoint{{emdash}}a collective wisdom of those who have similar perspectives in society which sought to heighten awareness to these marginalized groups and provide ways to improve their position in society.{{sfn|Hill Collins|2002}}{{sfn|Harnois|2020}}

Critical race theory draws on the priorities and perspectives of both critical legal studies and conventional civil rights scholarship, while also sharply contesting both of these fields. [[UC Davis School of Law]] legal scholar [[Angela P. Harris]], describes critical race theory as sharing "a commitment to a vision of liberation from racism through right reason" with the civil rights tradition.{{sfn|Harris|1994|pp=741–743}} It [[deconstruction|deconstructs]] some premises and arguments of [[legal theory]] and simultaneously holds that legally constructed rights are incredibly important.{{sfnm |1a1=Crenshaw |1a2=Gotanda |1a3=Peller |1a4=Thomas |1y=1995 |1p=xxiv |1ps=: "To the emerging race crits, rights discourse held a social and transformative value in the context of racial subordination that transcended the narrower question of whether reliance on rights alone could bring about any determinate results" |2a1=Harris |2y=1994}}{{page needed|date=September 2016}} As described by Derrick Bell, critical race theory in Harris' view is committed to "radical [[critique]] of the law (which is [[Normative legal thought|normatively]] [[deconstruction]]ist) and... radical emancipation by the law (which is normatively reconstructionist)".{{sfn|Bell|1995|p=899}}

[[University of Edinburgh]] philosophy professor, [[Tommy J. Curry]] says that by 2009, the CRT perspective on a race as a social construct was accepted by "many race scholars" as a "commonsense view" that race is not "biologically grounded and natural."{{sfn|Curry|2009a|p=166}}<ref name="Gillborn 2020" /> Social construct is a term from social constructivism, whose roots can be traced to the early science wars, instigated in part by [[Thomas Kuhn]]'s 1962 ''[[The Structure of Scientific Revolutions]]''.{{sfn|Mallon|2007}} [[Ian Hacking]], a Canadian [[philosopher]] specializing in the [[philosophy of science]], describes how social construction has spread through the social sciences. He cites the social construction of race as an example, asking how race could be "constructed" better.{{sfn|Hacking|2003}}

== Common themes ==
Delgado and Stefancic list ten themes within critical race thought: a "critique of liberalism"; "storytelling/counterstorytelling and 'naming one's own reality'"; "revisionist interpretations of American civil rights law and progress"; "a greater understanding of the underpinnings of race and racism"; "structural determinism; race, sex, class, and their intersections"; "essentialism and anti-essentialism"; "cultural nationalism/separatism"; "legal institutions, critical pedagogy, and minorities in the bar"; and "criticism and self-criticism".{{sfn|Delgado|Stefancic|1993}}

* '''Critique of liberalism''': Critical race theory scholars question foundational liberal concepts such as Enlightenment [[rationalism]], [[legal equality]] and [[constitutional]] neutrality, and they challenge the [[incrementalist]] approach of traditional civil-rights discourse.{{sfn|Delgado|Stefancic|2017|p=3}} They favor a [[Race-conscious policy|race-conscious]] approach to [[social transformation]], critiquing liberal ideas such as [[affirmative action]], [[color blindness (race)|color-blindness]], [[role model]]ing, or the [[Meritocracy|merit principle]]{{sfn|Delgado|Stefancic|1993|p=462}} preferring [[Political organization|political organizing]], in contrast to liberalism's reliance on [[Rights-based approach to development|rights-based remedies]].{{examples|date=October 2021}} [[David Theo Goldberg]] describes how countries that adopt [[classical liberalism]]'s concepts of "individualism, equality, and freedom", such as the United States, and modern European countries, conceal [[structural racism]] in their cultures and languages, citing terms such as "[[Third World]]" and "[[wikt:primitive#Adjective|primitive]]".<ref name="Goldberg 1993">{{Cite book |last=Goldberg |first=David Theo |title=Racist Culture: Philosophy and the Politics of Meaning |date=1993 |publisher=Blackwell |isbn=978-0-631-18078-4}}</ref>{{rp|6-7}}{{pb}}Crenshaw traces the origins of the New Right use of the concept of color-blindness from the 1970s neoconservative think tanks to the [[presidency of Ronald Reagan|Ronald Reagan]] administration in the 1980s.{{sfn|Crenshaw|1988|p=103}} She described how prominent figures such as neoconservative scholar [[Thomas Sowell]]{{sfn|Crenshaw|1988|p=104-105}} and [[William Bradford Reynolds]],{{sfn|Crenshaw|1988|p=104}} who served as [[United States Department of Justice Civil Rights Division|Assistant Attorney General for the Civil Rights Division]] from 1981 to 1988,{{sfn|Crenshaw|1988|p=104}} called for "strictly color-blind policies."{{sfn|Crenshaw|1988|p=104-105}} Sowell and Reynolds, like many conservatives at that time, believed that the goal of equality of the races had already been achieved and therefore the race-specific civil rights movement was a "threat to democracy".{{sfn|Crenshaw|1988|p=104-105}} The color-blindness logic used in "reverse discrimination" arguments in the post-civil rights period is informed by a particular viewpoint on "equality of opportunity", as adopted by Sowell,{{sfn|Crenshaw|1988|p=106}} in which the state's role is limited to providing a level playing field not to promote equal distribution of resources. Crenshaw says that "equality of opportunity" in antidiscrimination law can have both an expansive and a restrictive aspect.{{sfn|Crenshaw|1988|p=106}} Sociologist [[Eduardo Bonilla-Silva]], author of ''Racism without Racists: Color-Blind Racism and the Persistence of Racial Inequality in America'', wrote in 2020 that the new, subtle form of racism is "color-blind racism". It is a more subtle kind of racism with new strategies including using abstract liberalism to decontextualize race; naturalizing outcomes, such as segregation in neighborhoods; attributing certain cultural practices to race; and "minimization of racism".{{sfn|Bonilla-Silva|2020}} {{pb}}In his influential 1984 article, Delgado challenged the liberal concept of meritocracy in civil rights scholarship.{{sfn|Alcoff|2021}} He questioned how the top articles in the most well-established journals were all written by white men.{{sfn|Delgado|1984}}{{sfn|Alcoff|2021}}

* '''Storytelling/counterstorytelling and 'naming one's own reality'":'''': The use of narrative ([[storytelling]]) to illuminate and explore [[lived experience]]s of [[racial oppression]].{{sfn|Delgado|Stefancic|1993}}{{examples|date=October 2021}} Empathetic fallacy refers to the belief that one can change a narrative by offering an alternative narrative in hopes that the listener's empathy will quickly and reliably take over. In this view, empathy is not enough to change racism as most people are not exposed to those different from themselves, and people mostly seek out information about their own group.{{sfn|Delgado|Stefancic|2017|pp=33–35}}{{examples|date=October 2021}}Bryan Brayboy has emphasized the [[Epistemology|epistemic]] importance of storytelling in [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Indigenous-American]] communities as superseding that of theory, and has proposed a Tribal Critical Race Theory (TribCrit). <ref name="Brayboy 2005">{{Cite journal |last=Brayboy |first=Bryan McKinley Jones |date=December 2005 |title=Toward a Tribal Critical Race Theory in Education |journal=The Urban Review |volume=37 |issue=5 |pages=425–446 |doi=10.1007/s11256-005-0018-y |s2cid=145515195 |issn=0042-0972}}</ref>
*'''Standpoint epistemology''': The view that a members of racial minority groups have a unique authority and ability to speak about racism. This is seen as undermining dominant narratives relating to racial inequality, such as legal neutrality and personal responsibility or [[bootstrapping]], through valuable first-hand accounts of the experience of racism.<ref>{{harvnb|Leonardo|2013|pp=603–604}}; {{harvnb|Ansell|2008|p=345}}.</ref>
* '''Revisionist interpretations of American civil rights law and progress:''' Interest convergence is a concept introduced by Bell in his 1980 ''Harvard Law Review'' article, "''Brown v. Board of Education'' and the Interest-Convergence Dilemma".{{sfn|Bell|1980}} In this article Bell described how he re-assessed the impact of the hundreds of NAACP LDF desegration cases he won from 1960 to 1966, and began to believe that in spite of his sincerity at the time, [[anti-discrimination law]] had not resulted in improving Black children's access to quality education.{{sfn|Wright|2021}} He listed and described how Supreme Court cases had gutted civil rights legislation which had resulted in Black students continuing to attend all Black schools that lacked adequate funding and resources.{{sfn|Bell|1980}} In examinng these SC cases Bell concluded that the only civil-rights legislation that was passed coincided with the self-interest of white people, which Bell termed ''interest convergence''.{{sfn|Bell|1980}}<ref name="Shih 2017">{{Cite news |last=Shih |first=David |date=2017-04-19 |title=A Theory To Better Understand Diversity, And Who Really Benefits |work=NPR |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/codeswitch/2017/04/19/523563345/a-theory-to-better-understand-diversity-and-who-really-benefits |access-date=2021-10-20 |department=Code Switch}}</ref><ref name="Ogbonnaya-Ogburu 2020">{{Cite journal |last=Ogbonnaya-Ogburu |first=Ihudiya Finda |last2=Smith |first2=Angela D. R. |last3=To |first3=Alexandra |last4=Toyama |first4=Kentaro |date=2020-04-21 |title=Critical Race Theory for HCI |url=https://doi.org/10.1145/3313831.3376392 |journal=Proceedings of the 2020 CHI Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems |series=CHI '20 |location=New York |publisher=Association for Computing Machinery |pages=1–16 |doi=10.1145/3313831.3376392 |isbn=978-1-4503-6708-0 |quote=Those with power rarely concede it without ''interest convergence''. Racism benefits some groups, and those groups are reluctant to move against it. They will take or allow anti-racist actions most often when it also confers them benefits. In the U.S. context, forward movement for civil rights has typically only occurred when it is materially in the interest of the White majority.}}</ref> One of the best-known examples of interest convergence is the way in which American geopolitics during the [[Cold War]] in the aftermath of [[World War II]] was a critical factor in the passage of civil rights legislation by both Republicans and Democrats. Bell clearly described this in numerous articles by Bell, including "Brown" and it was confirmed in the research and publications of legal scholar, [[Mary L. Dudziak]]. In her journal articles and her 2000 book ''Cold War Civil Rights''{{emdash}}based on newly-released documents{{emdash}}Dudziak's provided detailed evidence that it was in the interest of the United States to quell the negative international press about treatment of Black Americans when the majority of population of the newly-decolonized countries the U.S. was trying to attract to Western-style democracy, was not white. The U.S. sought to promote liberal values throughout Africa, Asia, and Latin America to prevent the Soviet Union from spreading communism.<ref>{{harvnb|Bell|1989}}; {{harvnb|Dudziak|2000}}.</ref> Dudziak described how the international press widely circulated stories of segregation and violence against Black Americans. The [[Moore's Ford lynchings]] where a World War II veteran was lynched, was particularly widespread.<ref>{{harvnb|Dudziak|2000}}; {{harvnb|Ioffe|2017}}.</ref> American allies followed stories of American racism through the international press, and the Soviets used stories of examples of racism against Black Americans as a vital part of their propaganda.{{sfn|Dudziak|2000}} Dudziak performed extensive [[archival research]] in the [[United States Department of State|U.S. Department of State]] and [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] and concluded that U.S. government support for civil-rights legislation "was motivated in part by the concern that racial discrimination harmed the United States' foreign relations".{{sfnm |1a1=Delgado |1a2=Stefancic |1y=1993 |2a1=Delgado |2a2=Stefancic |2y=2017 |2pp=25–26 |3a1=Dudziak |3y=1988}} When the [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] was called in to prevent [[Little Rock Nine|nine Black students]] from integrating the [[Little Rock Central High School]], the international press covered the story extensively.{{sfn|Dudziak|2000}} The then Secretary of State told President [[Dwight Eisenhower]] that the Little Rock situation was "ruining" American foreign policy, particularly in Asia and Africa.{{sfn|Dudziak|1997}} The U.S. UN ambassador told President Eisenhower that as two-thirds of the world's population was not white, he was witnessing their negative reactions to American racial discrimination. He suspected that the U.S. "lost several votes on the Chinese communist item because of Little Rock."{{sfn|Ioffe|2017}}
* '''Intersectional theory''': The examination of race, sex, class, [[national origin]], and [[sexual orientation]], and how their intersections play out in various settings, such as how the needs of a Latina are different from those of a Black male, and whose needs are promoted.{{sfnm |1a1=Delgado |1a2=Stefancic |1y=1993 |2a1=Delgado |2a2=Stefancic |2y=2012 |2pp=51–55}}{{explain|date=October 2021}}
* '''Essentialism vs. anti-essentialism''': Delgado and Stefancic write, "Scholars who write about these issues are concerned with the appropriate unit for analysis: Is the black community one, or many, communities? Do middle- and working-class African-Americans have different interests and needs? Do all oppressed peoples have something in common?" This is a look at the ways that oppressed groups may share in their oppression but also have different needs and values that need to be looked at differently. It is a question of how groups can be [[Essentialism|essentialized]] or are unable to be essentialized.{{sfnm |1a1=Delgado |1a2=Stefancic |1y=1993 |2a1=Delgado |2a2=Stefancic |2y=2017 |2pp=63–66}}{{explain|date=October 2021}}
* '''Structural determinism; race, sex, class, and their intersections''': Exploration of how "the structure of legal thought or culture influences its content" in a way that determines social outcomes.{{sfnm |1a1=Delgado |1a2=Stefancic |1y=1993 |2a1=Delgado |2a2=Stefancic |2y=2012 |2pp=26, 155}}{{examples|date=October 2021}}
* '''Cultural nationalism/separatism''': The exploration of more radical views that argue for [[Separatism|separation]] and [[Reparations (transitional justice)|reparations]] as a form of [[foreign aid]] (including [[black nationalism]]).{{sfn|Delgado|Stefancic|1993}}{{examples|date=October 2021}}
* '''Legal institutions, critical pedagogy, and minorities in the bar:''' Camara Phyllis Jones defines [[institutionalized racism]] as "differential access to the goods, services, and opportunities of society by race. Institutionalized racism is [[normative]], sometimes [[Legalization (international law)|legalized]] and often manifests as inherited disadvantage. It is [[Structuralism|structural]], having been absorbed into our [[institution]]s of custom, practice, and law, so there need not be an identifiable offender. Indeed, institutionalized racism is often evident as inaction in the face of need, manifesting itself both in material conditions and in access to power. With regard to the former, examples include differential access to quality education, sound [[housing]], [[gainful employment]], appropriate medical facilities, and a clean environment."{{sfn|Jones|2002|pp=9–10}}

== Applications ==
Scholars of critical race theory have focused, with some particularity, on the issues of [[hate crime]] and [[hate speech]]. In response to the opinion of the [[US Supreme Court|U.S. Supreme Court]] in the hate speech case of ''[[R.A.V. v. City of St. Paul]]'' (1992), in which the Court struck down an anti-[[bias]] ordinance as applied to a teenager who had burned a cross, Mari Matsuda and Charles Lawrence argued that the Court had paid insufficient attention to the history of racist speech and the actual injury produced by such speech.<ref name="Matsuda 1993">{{cite book |last1=Matsuda |first1=Mari J. |last2=Lawrence |first2=Charles R. |title=Words That Wound: Critical Race Theory, Assaultive Speech, And The First Amendment |date=1993 |publisher=Westview Press |isbn=978-0-429-50294-1 |pages=133-136 |edition=1st |chapter=Epilogue: Burning Crosses and the R. A. V. Case}}</ref>

Critical race theorists have also argued in favor of affirmative action. They propose that so-called merit standards for hiring and educational admissions are not race-neutral and that such standards are part of the rhetoric of [[Neutrality (philosophy)|neutrality]] through which whites justify their disproportionate share of resources and social benefits.{{sfnm |1a1=Delgado |1y=1995 |2a1=Kennedy |2y=1990 |3a1=Williams |3y=1991}}

In his 2009 article "Will the Real CRT Please Stand Up: The Dangers of Philosophical Contributions to CRT", Curry distinguished between the original CRT key writings and what is being done in the name of CRT by a "growing number of white feminists".{{sfn|Curry|2009b|p=1}} The new CRT movement "favors narratives that inculcate the ideals of a post-racial humanity and racial amelioration between compassionate (Black and white) philosophical thinkers dedicated to solving America's race problem."{{sfn|Curry|2009b|p=2}} They are interested in [[discourse]] (i.e., how individuals speak about race) and the theories of white [[Continental philosophy|Continental philosophers]], over and against the structural and institutional accounts of [[White supremacy#Academic use of the term|white supremacy]] which were at the heart of the [[Realistic conflict theory|realist]] analysis of racism introduced in Derrick Bell's early works,{{sfn|Curry|2012}}{{page needed|date=September 2016}} and articulated through such Black thinkers as W. E. B. Du Bois, [[Paul Robeson]], and Judge [[Robert L. Carter]].{{sfn|Curry|2009b}}{{page needed|date=September 2016}}

== Academic and political criticism ==
According to the ''[[Encyclopaedia Britannica]]'', aspects of CRT have been criticized by "legal scholars and jurists from across the political spectrum."{{sfn|The Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica|2021}} Criticism of CRT has focused on its emphasis on storytelling, its critique of the merit principle and of objective truth, and its thesis of the ''[[voice of color]]''.{{sfn|Delgado|Stefancic|2017|p=102}} Critics say it contains a "[[postmodernism|postmodernist]]-inspired skepticism of objectivity and truth", and has a tendency to interpret "any racial inequity or imbalance [...] as proof of institutional racism and as grounds for directly imposing racially equitable outcomes in those realms", according to ''Britannica''. Proponents of CRT have also been accused of treating even well-meaning criticism of CRT as evidence of latent racism.{{sfn|The Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica|2021}}

In a 1997 book, law professors [[Daniel A. Farber]] and [[Suzanna Sherry]] criticized CRT for basing its claims on personal narrative and for its lack of testable [[hypotheses]] and measurable data.<ref>{{harvnb|Cabrera|2018|p=213}}; {{harvnb|Farber|Sherry|1997a}}.</ref>
CRT scholars including Crenshaw, Delgado, and Stefancic responded that such critiques represent dominant modes within social science which tend to exclude people of color.{{sfn|Cabrera|2018|p=213}} Delgado and Stefancic wrote that "In these realms [social science and politics], truth is a social construct created to suit the purposes of the dominant group."{{sfn|Cabrera|2018|p=213}} 
Farber and Sherry have also argued that anti-meritocratic tenets in critical race theory, critical feminism, and critical legal studies may unintentionally lead to [[antisemitic]] and [[Racism in the United States#Asian Americans|anti-Asian]] implications.<ref name="Hernández-Truyol 2006">{{cite journal |last1=Hernández-Truyol |first1=Berta E. |last2=Harris |first2=Angela P. |last3=Valdes |first3=Francisco |title=Beyond the First Decade: A Forward-Looking History of LatCrit Theory, Community and Praxis |journal=Berkeley la Raza Law Journal |date=2006 |url=https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2666047 |publisher=Social Science Research Network |ssrn=2666047 |access-date=January 9, 2021 |archive-date=June 17, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210617122949/https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2666047 |url-status=}}</ref><ref name="Farber & Sherry 1995">{{cite journal |last1=Farber |first1=Daniel A. |last2=Sherry |first2=Suzanna |title=Is the Radical Critique of Merit Anti-Semitic? |journal=California Law Review |date=May 1995 |volume=83 |issue=3 |pages=853 |doi=10.2307/3480866 |jstor=3480866 |quote=Therefore, the authors suggest, the radical critique of merit has the wholly unintended consequence of being anti-Semitic and possibly racist. |hdl=1803/6607 |hdl-access=free}}</ref>
They write that the success of Jews and Asians within what critical race theorists posit to be a structurally unfair system may lend itself to allegations of cheating and advantage-taking.{{sfn|Farber|Sherry|1997a}} 
In response, Delgado and Stefancic write that there is a difference between criticizing an unfair system and criticizing individuals who perform well inside that system.{{sfn|Delgado|Stefancic|2017|pp=103–104}}

===Public controversies===

==== Australia ====
In June 2021, following media reports that the proposed [[Australian Curriculum|national curriculum]] was "preoccupied with the oppression, discrimination and struggles of [[Indigenous Australians]]", the [[Australian Senate]] approved a motion tabled by right-wing senator [[Pauline Hanson]] calling on the federal government to reject CRT, despite it not being included in the curriculum.<ref name="Gatwiri 2021">{{cite web |last1=Gatwiri |first1=Kathomi |last2=Anderson |first2=Leticia |title=The Senate has voted to reject critical race theory from the national curriculum. What is it, and why does it matter? |website=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]] |date=June 22, 2021 |url=http://theconversation.com/the-senate-has-voted-to-reject-critical-race-theory-from-the-national-curriculum-what-is-it-and-why-does-it-matter-163102 |access-date=June 25, 2021}}</ref>

==== United Kingdom ====
[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] within the UK government began to criticize CRT in late 2020.<ref name="Ducey 2021">{{cite book |last1=Ducey |first1=Kimberley |last2=Feagin |first2=Joe R. |title=Revealing Britain's Systemic Racism: The Case of Meghan Markle and the Royal Family |date=2021 |publisher=Routledge |location=New York |isbn=978-1-000-38010-1 |chapter=Preface}}{{Page needed|date=November 2021}}</ref> Equalities Minister [[Kemi Badenoch]], who is of [[Nigerians|Nigerian]] descent, said during a parliamentary debate to mark [[Black History Month]]:

{{quote|We do not want to see teachers teaching their pupils about white privilege and inherited racial guilt{{nbsp}} [...] Any school which teaches these elements of critical race theory, or which promotes partisan political views such as defunding the police without offering a balanced treatment of opposing views, is breaking the law."{{r|Ducey 2021}}}}

In an open letter, 101 writers of the Black Writers' Guild denounced Badenoch for remarks about popular anti-racism books such as ''[[White Fragility]]'' and ''[[Why I'm No Longer Talking to White People About Race]]'', made in an interview in ''[[The Spectator]]'', in which she said, "many of these books{{emdash}}and, in fact, some of the authors and proponents of critical race theory{{emdash}}actually want a segregated society".<ref name="Cain">{{Cite news |last=Cain |first=Sian |date=October 30, 2020 |title=Writers protest after minister suggests anti-racism books support segregation |url=http://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/oct/30/writers-protest-after-minister-suggests-anti-racism-books-support-segregation |website=The Guardian |archive-date=October 30, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201030135153/https://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/oct/30/writers-protest-after-minister-suggests-anti-racism-books-support-segregation |url-status=}}</ref>

==== United States ====
Critical race theory has stirred controversy in the United States for promoting the use of [[narrative]] in [[legal studies]], advocating "legal [[instrumentalism]]" as opposed to ideal-driven uses of the law, and encouraging [[legal scholar]]s to promote racial equity.{{sfn|Ansell|2008|pp=345–346}} 

Before 1993, the term "critical race theory" was not part of public discourse.{{sfn|Harris|2021}} In the spring of that year, conservatives launched a campaign led by [[Clint Bolick]]{{sfn|Holmes|1997}} to portray [[Lani Guinier]]{{emdash}}then-President [[Bill Clinton]]'s nominee for [[United States Assistant Attorney General|Assistant Attorney General]] for [[United States Department of Justice Civil Rights Division|Civil Rights]]{{emdash}}as a radical because of her connection to CRT. Within months, Clinton had withdrawn the nomination,<ref>{{harvnb|Harris|2021}}; {{harvnb|Locin|Tackett|1993}}.</ref> describing the effort to stop Guinier's appointment as "a campaign of right-wing distortion and vilification."<ref name="Apple 1993">{{cite news |last=Apple |first=R. W. |title=The Guinier Battle: President Blames Himself for Furor Over Nominee |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/06/05/us/the-guinier-battle-president-blames-himself-for-furor-over-nominee.html |access-date=12 February 2014 |newspaper=The New York Times |page=1,1 |date=5 June 1993 |url-access=limited}}</ref>

Legal scholar [[Jeffrey Rosen (legal academic)|Jeffrey Rosen]] calls attorney [[Johnnie Cochran]]'s defense in the mid-1990s [[O. J. Simpson murder case]] as "applied critical race theory", the "most striking example" of CRT's influence on the U.S. legal system.{{sfn|Rosen|1996}} Law professor [[Margaret M. Russell]] responded to Rosen's assertion in the ''[[Michigan Law Review]]'', saying that Cochran's "dramatic" and "controversial" courtroom "style and strategic sense" in the Simpson case, resulted from his decades of experience as an attorney; it was not significantly influenced by CRT writings.{{sfn|Russell|1997|loc=Note 67, p. 791}} Ansell writes that the logic of legal instrumentalism "received its widest public reception" in the Simpson trial when Cochrane "adeptly enacted a sort of applied CRT" by selecting an African-American jury.{{sfn|Ansell|2008|p=346}} Cochran urged the jury to acquit Simpson in spite of the evidence against him as a form of [[jury nullification]].{{sfn|Ansell|2008|p=346}} 

In 2010, a [[Mexican American Studies Department Programs, Tucson Unified School District|Mexican-American studies program in Tucson, Arizona]], was halted because of a state law forbidding public schools from offering [[race-conscious]] education in the form of "advocat[ing] ethnic solidarity instead of the treatment of pupils as individuals".<ref name="Gillborn 2014">{{cite journal |last1=Gillborn |first1=David |title=Racism as Policy: A Critical Race Analysis of Education Reforms in the United States and England |journal=The Educational Forum |date=2014 |volume=78 |issue=1 |pages=30–31 |doi=10.1080/00131725.2014.850982 |s2cid=144670114 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/285890043 |via=ResearchGate}}</ref> Certain books, including a primer on CRT, were banned from the curriculum.{{r|Gillborn 2014}} [[Matt de la Peña]]'s young-adult novel ''[[Mexican WhiteBoy]]'' was banned for "containing 'critical race theory{{' "}} according to state officials.<ref name="Winnerip">{{cite news |last=Winerip |first=Michael |date=March 19, 2012 |title=Racial Lens Used to Cull Curriculum in Arizona |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/19/education/racial-lens-used-to-cull-curriculum-in-arizona.html |archive-date=July 8, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708111638/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/19/education/racial-lens-used-to-cull-curriculum-in-arizona.html |url-status= |url-access=limited}}</ref> The ban on ethnic-studies programs was later deemed unconstitutional on the grounds that the state showed discriminatory intent: "Both enactment and enforcement were motivated by racial animus", federal Judge [[A. Wallace Tashima]] ruled.<ref name="Depenbrock">{{Cite web |first=Julie |last=Depenbrock |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/ed/2017/08/22/545402866/federal-judge-finds-racism-behind-arizona-law-banning-ethnic-studies |title=Federal Judge Finds Racism Behind Arizona Law Banning Ethnic Studies |publisher=NPR |date=August 22, 2017 |archive-date=July 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706211502/https://www.npr.org/sections/ed/2017/08/22/545402866/federal-judge-finds-racism-behind-arizona-law-banning-ethnic-studies |url-status=}}</ref>

According to ''[[The Washington Post]]'', conservative lawmakers and activists have used the term "critical race theory" as a "catchall phrase for nearly any examination of systemic racism".{{r|Iati}} In the run-up to and aftermath of the [[2020 U.S. presidential election]], opposition to critical race theory was adopted as a campaign theme by [[Donald Trump]] and various conservative commentators on ''[[Fox News]]'' and right-wing talk radio shows.<ref>{{harvnb|Meyer|Severns|McGraw|2021}}; {{harvnb|Harris|2021}}.</ref> In September 2020, after seeing a piece on ''Fox News'' in which conservative activist [[Christopher Rufo]] denounced CRT,<ref name="Meckler">{{Cite news |last1=Meckler |first1=Laura |last2=Dawsey |first2=Josh |date=June 21, 2021 |title=Republicans, spurred by an unlikely figure, see political promise in critical race theory |work=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2021/06/19/critical-race-theory-rufo-republicans/ |url-status= |url-access=limited |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210621090847/https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2021/06/19/critical-race-theory-rufo-republicans/ |archive-date=June 21, 2021 |issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Trump issued an executive order directing agencies of the [[United States federal government]] to cancel funding for programs that mention "[[white privilege]]" or "critical race theory", on the basis that it constituted "divisive, un-American propaganda" and that it was "racist".<ref name="Dawsey">{{cite news |last1=Dawsey |first1=Josh |last2=Stein |first2=Jeff |title=White House directs federal agencies to cancel race-related training sessions it calls 'un-American propaganda' |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/09/04/white-house-racial-sensitivity-training/ |work=The Washington Post |date=September 5, 2020 |archive-date=September 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200911211815/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/09/04/white-house-racial-sensitivity-training/ |url-status= |issn=0190-8286 |url-access=limited}}</ref><ref name="Lang">{{cite news |last1=Lang |first1=Cady |title=What Is Critical Race Theory? |url=https://time.com/5891138/critical-race-theory-explained/ |work=Time |date=September 29, 2020 |archive-date=January 16, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210116030001/https://time.com/5891138/critical-race-theory-explained/ |url-status=}}</ref><ref name="Trump EO">{{cite web |author=Trump, Donald J. |title=Executive Order on Combating Race and Sex Stereotyping |date=September 22, 2020 |publisher=The White House |url=https://trumpwhitehouse.archives.gov/presidential-actions/executive-order-combating-race-sex-stereotyping/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210225215527/https://trumpwhitehouse.archives.gov/presidential-actions/executive-order-combating-race-sex-stereotyping/ |archive-date=February 25, 2021}}</ref> Rufo wrote on [[Twitter]], "The goal is to have the public read something crazy in the newspaper and immediately think 'critical race theory'."<ref name="Iati">{{cite news |last1=Iati |first1=Marisa |title=What is critical race theory, and why do Republicans want to ban it in schools? |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2021/05/29/critical-race-theory-bans-schools/ |work=The Washington Post |issn=0190-8286 |date=May 29, 2021 |url-access=limited}}</ref><ref name="Wallace-Wells">{{Cite magazine |last=Wallace-Wells |first=Benjamin |date=June 18, 2021 |title=How a Conservative Activist Invented the Conflict Over Critical Race Theory |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/annals-of-inquiry/how-a-conservative-activist-invented-the-conflict-over-critical-race-theory |url-status= |magazine=The New Yorker |url-access=limited |archive-date=June 18, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210618140627/https://www.newyorker.com/news/annals-of-inquiry/how-a-conservative-activist-invented-the-conflict-over-critical-race-theory |oclc=909782404}}</ref><ref name="Kingkade">{{cite web |last1=Kingkade |first1=Tyler |last2=Zadrozny |first2=Brandy |author-link2=Brandy Zadrozny |last3=Collins |first3=Ben |date=June 15, 2021 |title='Held hostage': How critical race theory moved from Fox News to school boards |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/critical-race-theory-invades-school-boards-help-conservative-groups-n1270794 |url-status= |website=NBC News |archive-date=June 16, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210616033841/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/critical-race-theory-invades-school-boards-help-conservative-groups-n1270794}}</ref>

In a speech on September 17, 2020, Trump denounced critical race theory and announced the formation of the [[1776 Commission]] to promote "patriotic education".<ref name="Wise">{{cite web |last=Wise |first=Alana |title=Trump Announces 'Patriotic Education' Commission, A Largely Political Move |website=[[NPR]] |date=September 17, 2020 |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/09/17/914127266/trump-announces-patriotic-education-commission-a-largely-political-move |archive-date=November 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201117231424/https://www.npr.org/2020/09/17/914127266/trump-announces-patriotic-education-commission-a-largely-political-move |url-status=}}</ref> On January 20, 2021, [[Joe Biden]] rescinded Trump's order<ref name="Guynn">{{cite web |last=Guynn |first=Jessica |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2021/01/20/biden-executive-order-overturns-trump-diversity-training-ban/4236891001/ |title=President Joe Biden rescinds Donald Trump ban on diversity training about systemic racism |work=USA Today |archive-date=May 12, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210512183506/https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2021/01/20/biden-executive-order-overturns-trump-diversity-training-ban/4236891001/ |url-status=}}</ref> and dissolved the 1776 Commission.<ref name="Kelly">{{cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2021/01/20/politics/biden-rescind-1776-commission-executive-order/index.html |publisher=CNN |title=Biden rescinds 1776 commission via executive order |last=Kelly |first=Caroline |date=January 20, 2021 |archive-date=January 20, 2021 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20210120121853/https://edition.cnn.com/2021/01/20/politics/biden-rescind-1776-commission-executive-order/index.html}}</ref> Opposition to what was purported to be critical race theory was subsequently adopted as a major theme by several conservative think tanks and pressure groups, including the [[Heritage Foundation]], the [[Idaho Freedom Foundation]] and the [[American Legislative Exchange Council]].<ref name="Greenfield" /><ref name="Kingkade" />

====== State-level legislation ======
{{Main|Censoring of school curricula in the United States}}
In early 2021, bills were introduced to restrict teaching critical race theory in public schools,<ref name="O'Kane">{{cite web |last=O'Kane |first=Caitlin |title=Nearly a dozen states want to ban critical race theory in schools |date=May 21, 2021 |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/critical-race-theory-state-bans/ |archive-date=June 13, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210613004743/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/critical-race-theory-state-bans/ |url-status= |website=CBS News}}</ref> including [[Idaho]], [[Iowa]], [[Oklahoma]], [[Tennessee]] and [[Texas]].<ref name="Waxman">{{cite news |last1=Waxman |first1=Olivia |title='Critical Race Theory Is Simply the Latest Bogeyman.' Inside the Fight Over What Kids Learn About America's History |url=https://time.com/6075193/critical-race-theory-debate/ |work=Time |date=24 June 2021 |url-access=limited}}</ref> Several of these bills specifically mention "critical race theory" or single out the ''[[New York Times]]'' [[1619 Project]]. CRT is only taught at a [[university]] level, though some lower-level curricula have reflected basic themes of CRT.{{sfn|The Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica|2021}}{{r|Iati}}{{Example needed|s|date=November 2021}}

In mid-April 2021, a bill was introduced in the Idaho legislature that would effectively ban any educational entity from teaching or advocating [[sectarianism]], including critical race theory or other programs involving social justice.<ref name="Richert">{{cite web |last1=Richert |first1=Kevin |last2=Jones |first2=Blake |date=April 19, 2021 |title=Legislative roundup, 4.19.21: New bill targets sectarianism, critical race theory |url=https://www.idahoednews.org/legislature/legislative-roundup-4-19-21-a-bill-targeting-instruction-on-sectarianism-surfaces/ |website=Idaho Education News |archive-date=April 19, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210419204506/https://www.idahoednews.org/legislature/legislative-roundup-4-19-21-a-bill-targeting-instruction-on-sectarianism-surfaces/ |url-status=}}</ref> On May 4, 2021, the bill was signed into law by Governor [[Brad Little]].<ref name="Adams B">{{cite web |last=Adams |first=Biba |url=https://news.yahoo.com/bill-banning-critical-race-theory-124451511.html |title=Bill banning critical race theory in public schools becomes law |work=Yahoo News |date=May 4, 2021 |archive-date=May 6, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210506205741/https://news.yahoo.com/bill-banning-critical-race-theory-124451511.html |url-status=}}</ref> On June 10, 2021, the Florida State Board of Education unanimously voted to ban public schools from teaching critical race theory at the urging of governor [[Ron DeSantis]].<ref name="Postal">{{cite web |last=Postal |first=Leslie |title=Florida board votes to ban "critical race theory" from state classrooms |work=Orlando Sentinel |date=June 10, 2021 |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/education/os-ne-critical-race-state-board-20210610-7pzv23n7rjeixi3a4veffugalq-story.html |archive-date=June 12, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210612150641/https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/education/os-ne-critical-race-state-board-20210610-7pzv23n7rjeixi3a4veffugalq-story.html |url-status=}}</ref> As of July 2021, 10 U.S. states have introduced bills or taken other steps that would restrict teaching critical race theory, and 26 others were in the process of doing so.<ref name="Schwartz">{{Cite web |last=Schwartz |first=Sarah |date=2021-06-11 |title=Map: Where Critical Race Theory Is Under Attack |url=https://www.edweek.org/policy-politics/map-where-critical-race-theory-is-under-attack/2021/06 |url-status= |access-date=2021-07-13 |website=Education Week}}</ref><ref name="Greenfield">{{cite web |last=Greenfield |first=Nathan M. |date=June 12, 2021 |title=Why are states lining up to ban critical race theory? |url=https://www.universityworldnews.com/post.php?story=20210612085115831 |url-status= |website=[[University World News]] |archive-date=June 13, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210613232641/https://www.universityworldnews.com/post.php?story=20210612085115831}}</ref> In June 2021, the [[American Association of University Professors]], the [[American Historical Association]], the [[Association of American Colleges and Universities]], and [[PEN America]] released a joint statement stating their opposition to such legislation, and by August 2021, 167 [[Professional association|professional organizations]] had signed onto the statement.{{sfn|American Historical Association|2021}} In August 2021, the [[Brookings Institution]] recorded that eight states{{emdash}}Idaho, Oklahoma, Tennessee, Texas, Iowa, New Hampshire, Arizona, and South Carolina{{emdash}}had passed regulation on the issue, though also noted that none of the bills that passed, with the exception of Idaho's, actually contained the words "critical race theory." Brookings also noted that these laws often extend beyond race to discussions of [[Gender studies|gender]].<ref name="Ray">{{Cite web |last1=Ray |last2=Gibbons |first1=Rashawn |first2=Alexandra |date=2021-07-02 |title=Why are states banning critical race theory? |url=https://www.brookings.edu/blog/fixgov/2021/07/02/why-are-states-banning-critical-race-theory/ |access-date=2021-10-31 |publisher=Brookings Institution}}</ref> Critics{{Who|date=November 2021}} have called the state laws a [[Memory laws|memory law]] and a confirmation of the idea that racism is codified into the law of the United States.<ref name="Snyder">{{Cite news |last=Snyder |first=Timothy |date=2021-06-29 |title=The War on History Is a War on Democracy |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/06/29/magazine/memory-laws.html |access-date=2021-10-31 |issn=0362-4331 |url-access=limited}}</ref>

== Subfields ==
Within critical race theory, various sub-groupings focus on issues and nuances unique to particular ethno-racial and/or marginalized communities. This includes the intersection of race with disability, ethnicity, gender, sexuality, class, or religion. For example, disability critical race studies (DisCrit), critical race feminism (CRF), Hebrew Crit (HebCrit), Black Critical Race Theory (Black Crit), Latino critical race studies (LatCrit<ref>{{harvnb|Yosso|2005|p=72}}; {{harvnb|Delgado|Stefancic|1998b}}.</ref>), Asian American critical race studies (AsianCrit{{sfn|Yosso|2005|p=72}}), South Asian American critical race studies (DesiCrit{{sfn|Harpalani|2013}}), and American Indian critical race studies (sometimes called TribalCrit{{sfn|Yosso|2005|p=72}}). CRT methodologies have also been applied to the study of white immigrant groups.{{sfn|Myslinska|2014a|pp=559–660}} CRT has spurred some scholars to call for a second wave of [[whiteness studies]], which is now a small offshoot known as Second Wave Whiteness (SWW).{{sfn|Jupp|Berry|Lensmire|2016}} Critical race theory has also begun to spawn research that looks at understandings of race outside the United States.{{sfn|Myslinska|2014b}}<ref>See e.g., {{harvnb|Levin|2008}}.</ref>

=== Disability critical race theory ===
Another offshoot field is [[Disability studies#Race|disability critical race studies]] (DisCrit), which combines [[disability studies]] and CRT to focus on the [[Intersectionality|intersection]] of disability and race.{{sfn|Annamma|Connor|Ferri|2012}}

=== Latino critical race theory ===

Latino critical race theory (LatCRT or LatCrit) is a research framework that outlines the social construction of race as central to how people of color are constrained and oppressed in society. Race scholars developed LatCRT as a critical response to the "problem of the [[Color line (racism)|color line]]" first explained by [[W. E. B. Du Bois]].{{sfn|Treviño|Harris|Wallace|2008}} While CRT focuses on the Black–White paradigm, LatCRT has moved to consider other racial groups, mainly [[Chicana/o studies|Chicana/Chicanos]], as well as [[Latinos/as]], [[Asian people|Asians]], [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]]/[[First Nations]], and women of color.

In ''Critical Race Counterstories along the Chicana/Chicano Educational Pipeline'', [[Tara J. Yosso]] discusses how the constraint of POC can be defined. Looking at the differences between [[Chicano|Chicana/o]] students, the tenets that separate such individuals are: the intercentricity of race and racism, the challenge of [[dominant ideology]], the commitment to [[social justice]], the centrality of [[Experiential knowledge|experience knowledge]], and the [[Interdisciplinarity|interdisciplinary]] perspective.{{sfn|Yosso|2006|p=7}}

LatCRTs main focus is to advocate social justice for those living in [[social exclusion|marginalized communities]] (specifically Chicana/os), who are guided by structural arrangements that disadvantage people of color. [[Institution|Social institutions]] function as [[Dispossession, oppression and depression|dispossessions]], [[Disfranchisement|disenfranchisement]], and discrimination over minority groups, while LatCRT seeks to give voice to those who are [[victimized]].{{sfn|Treviño|Harris|Wallace|2008}} In order to do so, LatCRT has created two common themes:

First, CRT proposes that white supremacy and racial power are maintained over time, a process that the law plays a central role in. Different racial groups lack the voice to speak in this [[civil society]], and, as such, CRT has introduced a new critical form of expression, called the ''voice of color''.{{sfn|Treviño|Harris|Wallace|2008}} The voice of color is narratives and storytelling [[monologue]]s used as devices for conveying personal racial experiences. These are also used to counter [[metanarrative]]s that continue to maintain [[racial inequality]]. Therefore, the experiences of the oppressed are important aspects for developing a LatCRT analytical approach, and it has not been since the rise of slavery that an institution has so fundamentally shaped the life opportunities of those who bear the label of criminal.

Secondly, LatCRT work has investigated the possibility of transforming the relationship between [[law enforcement]] and racial power, as well as pursuing a project of achieving racial emancipation and anti-subordination more broadly.{{sfn|Yosso|2005}} Its body of research is distinct from general critical race theory in that it emphasizes immigration theory and policy, language rights, and accent- and national origin-based forms of discrimination.{{sfn|Delgado|Stefancic|2001|p=6}} CRT finds the experiential knowledge of people of color and draws explicitly from these lived experiences as data, presenting research findings through storytelling, chronicles, scenarios, narratives, and parables.{{sfn|Yosso|2006}}

=== Asian critical race theory ===
Asian critical race theory looks at the influence of race and racism on Asian Americans and their experiences in the U.S. education system.<ref name="Iftikar 2018">{{Cite journal |last1=Iftikar |first1=Jon S. |last2=Museus |first2=Samuel D. |date=November 26, 2018 |title=On the utility of Asian critical (AsianCrit) theory in the field of education |journal=International Journal of Qualitative Studies in Education |volume=31 |issue=10 |pages=935–949 |doi=10.1080/09518398.2018.1522008 |s2cid=149949621}}</ref> Like Latino critical race theory, Asian critical race theory is distinct from the main body of CRT in its emphasis on immigration theory and policy.{{sfn|Delgado|Stefancic|2001|p=6}}

===Critical Philosophy of Race===
The Critical Philosophy of Race (CPR) is inspired by both Critical Legal Studies and Critical Race Theory's use of interdisciplinary scholarship. Both CLS and CRT explore the covert nature of mainstream use of "apparently neutral concepts, such as merit or freedom."{{sfn|Alcoff|2021}}

